<!-- THERMOELECTRIC VS COMPRESSOR -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Know Your Unit</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Thermoelectric vs compressor, matters more in LA than most cities</h2>
    <p class="lead">LA's warm climate makes this distinction critical. A thermoelectric unit that "isn't cooling" may not be broken at all, it may simply be placed in a room that's too warm for it to function correctly.</p>

    <div class="compare-grid">
      <div class="compare-card">
        <div class="compare-badge badge-thermo">Thermoelectric</div>
        <h3>Thermoelectric Wine Coolers</h3>
        <p>Use a Peltier module to transfer heat, no compressor, no refrigerant, no moving parts. Very quiet and vibration-free, which matters for sediment-sensitive aged wines. Critical limitation: can only cool approximately 20°F below ambient room temperature.</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem; color:#c88080; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:12px;">⚠️ In a LA room at 80°F, these units can only reach ~60°F, not the ideal 55°F storage temperature.</p>
        <ul class="compare-list pro">
          <li>No vibration, safe for aged bottles</li>
          <li>Near-silent operation</li>
          <li>Lower energy consumption</li>
          <li>No refrigerant, simpler repair</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="compare-list con" style="margin-top:8px;">
          <li>Struggles in warm rooms above 75°F</li>
          <li>Cannot maintain temp in hot weather</li>
          <li>Not suitable for unconditioned spaces</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-card">
        <div class="compare-badge badge-comp">Compressor</div>
        <h3>Compressor Wine Coolers</h3>
        <p>Work like a small refrigerator, compressor, refrigerant, condenser coils. Can maintain 55°F regardless of ambient room temperature, making them far more reliable in LA's warm climate. More components means more possible failure points, but the failure modes are well-understood.</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem; color:#80c880; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:12px;">✓ Recommended for LA homes, can maintain wine storage temperature year-round.</p>
        <ul class="compare-list pro">
          <li>Maintains temperature in any ambient</li>
          <li>Reliable in LA's warm climate</li>
          <li>Handles large collections</li>
          <li>Can reach lower temperatures</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="compare-list con" style="margin-top:8px;">
          <li>Some vibration (minimal on quality units)</li>
          <li>More components to potentially fail</li>
          <li>Higher energy consumption</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose and fix</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Cooling (Compressor Units)</h3>
        <p>The condenser fan, thermostat, compressor, or a refrigerant issue are the likely causes. We diagnose systematically, a condenser fan failure is inexpensive; a compressor replacement on a premium unit is a more significant decision. We give you a written estimate and an honest assessment of repair vs. replace before anything is touched.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Cooling (Thermoelectric Units)</h3>
        <p>First question: what is the ambient room temperature where the unit is located? Thermoelectric units cannot cool more than ~20°F below ambient. If the room is 78°F, the unit physically cannot reach 55°F regardless of whether it's working correctly. If the ambient is within spec, the Peltier module or its fan may have failed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Uneven Cooling Between Zones</h3>
        <p>Dual and multi-zone units have individual fans for each zone. When a zone fan motor fails, that zone loses active cooling while others remain cold. A door seal gap allowing warm air into one section, or a thermostat that's drifted in one zone, can also produce uneven temperatures. We test each zone independently.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Temperature Fluctuation</h3>
        <p>A thermostat that's cycling incorrectly, a door seal that isn't creating a consistent seal, or a condenser that's overworking in a warm room can all produce temperature swings. For a wine collection, consistent temperature matters as much as the absolute number, fluctuation accelerates aging and can cause corks to expand and contract.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Excessive Vibration / Loud Noise</h3>
        <p>A compressor that's wearing out, a loose condenser fan, or a poorly leveled unit can all produce vibration. For a serious wine collection, especially aged bottles with sediment, excessive vibration is worth fixing promptly. Vibration keeps sediment in suspension and disrupts the slow processes involved in wine maturation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Water Leaking / Condensation</h3>
        <p>A clogged condensate drain line is the most common cause of water pooling under or inside a wine cooler. A door seal that isn't seating properly allows humid air in, which condenses on the cold interior surfaces and eventually drips. Humidity control systems on premium units can also develop faults that produce condensation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Won't Turn On / Shuts Off</h3>
        <p>A failed control board, tripped thermal limiter, or power supply issue can cause a wine cooler to shut off or not start. On thermoelectric units, the Peltier module driver board is a common failure point. We carry control boards for Sub-Zero, U-Line, and Vinotemp specifically.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Seal Deterioration</h3>
        <p>A cracked or compressed door gasket lets warm air in continuously, forcing the cooler to work harder and eventually losing temperature. For thermoelectric units especially, a compromised door seal can push the unit past its cooling capacity. Gasket replacement is one of the better preventive investments on an otherwise healthy unit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Condenser Fan Dust Buildup</h3>
        <p>The single most common gradual-decline failure on a compressor wine cooler. Dust accumulation on the condenser fan blades and coil prevents heat rejection, the fan can't shed heat, the compressor runs longer, and the unit eventually can't hold temperature on a warm SoCal day. Annual cleaning of the condenser coil and fan blades with compressed air is the single best preventive-maintenance action you can take. We clear coils on every diagnostic visit at no extra charge.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top:36px; padding:24px; background:#fff; border:1px solid #e8e8e8; border-radius:8px;">
      <p style="font-size:0.78rem; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.12em; color:#888; margin:0 0 12px; font-weight:700;">Symptom-specific diagnostic guides</p>
      <ul style="list-style:none; padding:0; margin:0; display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit, minmax(220px, 1fr)); gap:10px;">
        <li><a href="/services/wine-cooler-repair/not-cooling/" style="color:#C8102E; font-weight:700; text-decoration:none;">Not Cooling</a> <span style="color:#666; font-size:0.9rem;">— compressor, thermostat, evap fan, refrigerant (EPA 608)</span></li>
        <li><a href="/services/wine-cooler-repair/temperature-fluctuating/" style="color:#C8102E; font-weight:700; text-decoration:none;">Temperature Fluctuating</a> <span style="color:#666; font-size:0.9rem;">— thermostat hysteresis, dual-zone cross-contamination</span></li>
        <li><a href="/services/wine-cooler-repair/door-seal-issues/" style="color:#C8102E; font-weight:700; text-decoration:none;">Door Seal Issues</a> <span style="color:#666; font-size:0.9rem;">— gasket compression, hinge sag, glass condensation</span></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- VIBRATION -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05, Vibration &amp; Your Wine Collection</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Why a noisy wine cooler matters more than a noisy refrigerator</h2>

    <div class="vibration-block">
      <div class="vib-label">🍷 Wine Collection Context</div>
      <h3>Vibration disturbs sediment and disrupts aging</h3>
      <p>Most appliance repair companies treat a wine cooler like a small refrigerator. For casual use with young commercial wines, that's fine. For a collection that includes aged bottles, anything 8+ years old, or bottles you're storing to age further, vibration is a genuine concern worth addressing.</p>
      <p>Wine aging involves slow chemical reactions and the gradual settling of tannins, tartrates, and other compounds into sediment. Vibration keeps those compounds suspended rather than allowing them to settle, can disturb the sediment layer in bottles that have already thrown it, and over years of chronic exposure may affect the flavor development of wines in maturation. This is the reason serious wine storage, cellars, EuroCave units, high-end undercounter coolers, specifies "vibration-free" as a design criterion.</p>
      <p>A wine cooler that's suddenly much louder or more vibration-prone than it used to be, often the early sign of a failing compressor or loose fan mounting, is worth repairing promptly if the collection matters to you. Our technicians ask about the collection when we diagnose a wine cooler with vibration issues, because it affects how we prioritize the repair recommendation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

